summaries.title: Recognizing Privilege and Peer Disparities in Engineering Education
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Developing Academic Confidence Through Mentorship
summaries.summaryText: Daniel described feeling initially out of place in rigorous electrical engineering courses, particularly when comparing himself to peers with prior robotics or coding experience. His confidence improved after joining a peer mentoring program where upperclassmen provided guidance and reassurance. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Balancing Academic Rigor with Limited Peer Representation
summaries.summaryText: Maria described feeling academically capable but often isolated in her computer engineering courses, where few other Latina students were enrolled. She mentioned that faculty were supportive when approached, but that representation and group belonging remained low, especially during first-year lab sections. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Microaggressions and Invisible Labor in Group Dynamics
summaries.summaryText: Aaliyah recounted repeated experiences of having her technical input questioned in group settings. She also described taking on emotional labor to support other students facing similar bias. [Part 4/4]

themes.title: Normalizing Mental Health Conversations in STEM
themes.description: Sarahs work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 4]

themes.title: First-Generation Adaptation to STEM Rigor
themes.description: Luiss story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Team Diversity as an Engineering Strength
themes.description: Ethan believes interdisciplinary and culturally diverse teams drive better innovation outcomes, reflecting the growing importance of social awareness in engineering practice. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Marias reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Emotional Labor and Advocacy Burden in Underrepresented Students
themes.description: Aaliyahs experience illustrates how women of color in engineering often balance advocacy roles with academic demands, leading to invisible emotional labor that institutions rarely acknowledge. [Extended 2]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyahs mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students.
